\begin_layout Title
Tax on Unhealthy Foods
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
normalsize
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Tax on foods containing high amounts of saturated fats in Denmark from
 2009 to 2012
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
A.V.
 RIIS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
2013
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center

\emph on
Paper for the course Tax Policy in the European Union, College of Europe
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset toc
LatexCommand tableofcontents

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper will look at the introduction of a tax on food containing high
 amounts of saturated fat in Denmark in 2009.
 The issue of a tax on unhealthy foods plays into a broader debate of how
 policy can contribute to promote healthy eating and thus to increased public
 health meaning lower expenditures for public health services and higher
 productivity in the labour market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several ways to define unhealthy foods and, given that the ultimate
 purpose is improvement of public health, several intermediate objectives
 depending on the context.
 In Denmark the main concern was to reduce cancer and cardiovascular diseases
 in order to increase longevity, while the concern in the UK and US mainly
 relates to obesity.
 These two health concerns are undoubtedly intertwined, but for clarification
 purposes it is useful to keep the two different concerns in mind.
 The policy response also differs.
 Some talk about a tax on sugary soft drinks, while others, as in this paper,
 talk about a tax on saturated fat.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, to avoid confusion on the matter 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 1244"
key "caraher2005taxingfood"

\end_inset

 suggest that the terms 'food tax' and 'fat tax' be properly distinguished.
 A 'food tax' is thus understood as any surcharge on food, while a 'fat
 tax' is more limited in scope to specific foods containing high amounts
 of saturated fats.
 A tax on sugary soft drinks, which in this paper is used for comparison
 purposes falls under the broader category of a food tax.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another terminological clarification concerns the use of 'negative externality',
 which is used interchangably with 'diseconomies'.
 In the case of a tax on unhealthy foods the individual consumer in optimising
 own consumption fails to take into account, i.e.
 internalise, the full social cost of his or her consumption, which is increased
 health costs and fall in labour productivity.
 This failure to internalise the externalities implies suboptimal resource
 allocation, which can be improved by government intervention.
 Thus, from an economic point of view addressing public health risks such
 as obesity makes sense, because obesity has implications for health costs
 and labour market productivity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "pp. 6-7"
key "leicester2004thefat"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The market failure might arise because consumers systematically underestimate
 the negative effects the consumption of foods containing high amounts of
 saturated fats can have in the long-run.
 In this sense it is a problem of imperfect information as consumers do
 not have full information about the detrimental effects of consuming unhealthy
 foods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 145"
key "forebyggelseskommissionen2009vikan"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 150"
key "herrnstein1993utility"

\end_inset

 has identified this phenomenon as 'melioration' and defined it as the choosing
 of that alternative that yields the highest utility presently without taking
 into account the effect on future yields.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Background Information
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tax on products containing high amounts saturated fats
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Saturated fats are prevalent in dairy products such as milk, cheese and
 butter, and in meat 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 143"
key "forebyggelseskommissionen2009vikan"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 was originally adopted by the Danish liberal-conservative government in
 March 2009 as part of a package of reforms meant to lower the Danish labour
 income tax rate, in particular, the effective marginal tax rate and raising
 the work tax credit such that it becomes more profitable to work rather
 than staying on social welfare benefits 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "danishgovernment2009forrarspakke"

\end_inset

.
 The tax on saturated fats took effect from 1 October 2011 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "baekmark2012fedtog"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tax was originally proposed by the Prevention Commission (
\emph on
Fore\SpecialChar \-
byg\SpecialChar \-
gelses\SpecialChar \-
kom\SpecialChar \-
mis\SpecialChar \-
sion\SpecialChar \-
en
\emph default
) in 2009 according to whose calculations a tax on saturated fats of around
 €2.7 (DKK20) per kg would reduce the aggregate consumption of saturated
 fat with around three percent and thus prolonging the average life expectancy
 of newly born Dane with 0.003 years or a little more than one day (0.003*365=1.095
).
 In aggregated terms, the Prevention Commission estimated that the three
 procent reduction would add 3,800 years over the next ten years to the
 total living age of the Danish population 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "pp. 153-4"
key "forebyggelseskommissionen2009vikan"

\end_inset

.
 Eventually, the tax was put at DKK16 per kg and exempted food with a content
 of saturated fats below 2.3%.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
SKAT, ‘Ny afgift på mættet fedt i fødevarer’, 15 April 2011, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://www.skat.dk/SKAT.aspx?oId=1942614&vId=0"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Historically, food taxes have been a prime contributor to riots 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 1242"
key "caraher2005taxingfood"

\end_inset

.
 Although the response in the present case falls short of being properly
 designated as a riot, the tax was nonetheless the subject of a considerable
 controversy and even its original designers seemed to regret its coming
 into existence.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Martin Flink, ‘Upopulære afgifter svære at slippe af med’, Jyllands-Posten,
 16 June 2012, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://epn.dk/article4724606.ece"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Even before taking effect it met its first objections as some argued that
 the proposed tax was precluded under EU law, because it would function
 as an entry barrier for goods and products produced in other EU member
 states.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ritzau, ‘EU-sag truer regeringens fedtafgift’, Politiken, 27 December 2010,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://politiken.dk/tjek/tjekmad/produktion/ECE1152270/eu-sag-truer-regeringens-fedtafgift/"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One aspect of controversy concerning the tax was the impact on the Danish
 food industry as the tax caused, as the Prevension Commission already put
 it in 2009, not insignificant administrative burdens.
 Companies producing high-quality cheeses estimated that the price of their
 products would increase with 20-25%,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Michelle Arrouas, ‘Gourmetoste forsvinder fra hylderne med fedtskatten’,
 Politiken, 15 December 2010, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://politiken.dk/mad/madnyt/ECE1142214/gourmetoste-forsvinder-fra-hylderne-med-fedtskatten/"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 while the Danish association for slaughter houses complained that the tax
 would burden the butchers with a detrimental adminstrative burden, because
 they under the tax code was obliged to measure and label all their products
 with the amount of saturated fat.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ritzau, ‘Slagtere frygter ændret fedtafgift’, Politiken, 10 December 2010,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://politiken.dk/tjek/tjekmad/produktion/ECE1138890/slagtere-frygter-aendret-fedtafgift/"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For smaller, independent butcheries this could be tantamount to administrative
 asphyxiation, risking to force them to close.
 The association for slaughter houses even took the Danish government claiming
 that the tax would be inimical to the Danish food sector and employment
 in general.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Marie Ravn Nielsen, ‘Slagtermestre stævner staten over fedtafgift’, DR.dk,
 20 December 2011, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://www.dr.dk/Nyheder/Indland/2011/12/20/160828.htm"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But producers were not the only group criticising the new tax.
 It was also argued the tax was socially skewed in the sense that people
 with lower income was hit proportionally higher by the tax than higher
 income individuals.
 In particular, calculations made by the interest organisation for the agricultu
ral and food industry in Denmark, the Danish Agricultural & Food Council,
 showed that single parents were proportionally harder hit by the tax than
 other population groups.
 The annual food expenditures of a household with a single parent with two
 children would increase by €136.28 (DKK1,016.00) compared with a household
 of two adults and two children that would experience an increase per adult
 of €219.98/2=€109.945 (DKK1,640.00/2=DKK820.00).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Marianne Søndergaard, ‘Sukker- og fedtafgift rammer enlige med børn’, Foodcultur
e.dk, 6 July 2012, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://tinyurl.com/foodculture12"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nonetheless, the tax was not only met with resistance.
 The Danish Association of Doctors claimed that the tax was actually contributin
g to the improvement of national health.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Flemming Steen Pedersen, ‘Læger: Afgift på usund mad virker’, Berlingske.dk,
 5 November 2012, http://www.b.dk/nationalt/laeger-afgift-paa-usund-mad-virker-0.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Other sources confirm that the consumption of butter, margarine and cooking
 oil was decreased after the introduction of the tax.
\begin_inset Foot
