\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Economic Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a starting point for the economic analysis, the opening sentence of Diamond
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "diamond1973consumption"

\end_inset

 seems pertinent: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

In the presence of consumption externalities a natural first response to
 improve resource allocation is corrective pricing (...).
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 He proceeds to mention that a Pareto optimal allocation can be achieved
 by levying corrective surcharges above the marginal production cost, which
 is what the Danish tax on unhealthy food can be seen as an example of.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, the tax in question does not vary according to the externalities
 from consuming unhealthy foods, so it can be defined as a uniform corrective
 surcharge.
 For some people it is proportionally more unhealthy to consume fatty and
 sugary foods, but it is for practical reasons not possible to take these
 individual characteristic into account when taxing unhealthy food.
 This effect was in fact already anticipated by the Danish Prevention Commission
 who originally fathered the proposal on saturated fats 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 153"
key "forebyggelseskommissionen2009vikan"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the longer run, consuming unhealthy foods have the negative externality
 of imposing additional burdens on the health sector.
 The demand for hospital services does thus vary with the externalities.
 Given this and the fact the the corrective surcharge is uniform, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "diamond1973consumption"

\end_inset

 writes that we cannot achieve Pareto optimality.
 It is, in other words, impossible to levy exactly the amount of tax that
 corresponds to the additional burden imposed on the health sector from
 consuming unhealthy foods for each and every individual.
 An obvious modification is to levy a weighted average of externalities,
 where the weights are the price elasticities of demand for health services.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This modification does, however, not work under certain circumstances.
 Diamond 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
after "p. 527"
key "diamond1973consumption"

\end_inset

 argues that it is possible, if not also plausible, that some consumer's
 demand will rise with the corrective tax and that this aggregate increase
 in demand exceeds the fall in demand as a result of the direct effect of
 the price rise.
 In this case the weights given are both positive and negative and might
 thus not correspond to the externalities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the example of the tax on unhealthy foods, it could be argued that the
 demands for health services will increase if less unhealthy food is eaten,
 although if consumption is shifted to other unhealthy foods that are not
 sugary or fatty, this could be the case.
 Indeed, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "astrup2011therole"

\end_inset

 concluded in their study on saturated fats that we do not know 
\emph on
per se
\emph default
 whether saturated fats cause diseases.
 Furthermore they concluded that reducing the intake of saturated fats only
 is effective if replaced with whole grain products or unsaturated fats
 from fish and plants.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Thomas Hoffmann, ‘Fedtskat undermineret af ny forskning’, Videnskab.dk, 7
 February 2011, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://videnskab.dk/krop-sundhed/fedtskat-undermineret-af-ny-forskning"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Taxing one type of unhealthy food such as those containing saturated fats
 to improve public health works only to the extent that people do not simply
 substitute their consumption to goods that are equally unhealthy.
 Elsewhere it has been argued that the problem is excessive calory intake
 
\emph on
per se
\emph default
 that poses the greatest health risk, so merely taxing one type of unhealthy
 food is unlikely to improve public health significantly.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Stephen Gandel, ‘Denmark Levies First-Ever Fat Tax, Should the U.S.?’, Time,
 accessed 26 March 2013, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://business.time.com/2011/10/05/denmark-levies-first-ever-fat-tax-should-the-u-s/"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The argument above implies that it is plausible that a tax on saturated
 fats would in fact decrease public health, i.e.
 increase the demand for health services, if it is not replaced with healthier
 food or even replaced with other types of unhealthy food.
 Hence, it would not suffice to simply levy the a weighted average of externalit
ies in the case of a tax on saturated fat to achieve Pareto optimality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The argument above relies on the assumption that the demand for health services
 will vary with the negative externalities generated by consuming unhealthy
 foods.
 In fact, Diamond (1973) investigates the case where the externalities generated
 affects the demand for the good itself.
 The question then is whether the demand for foods containing saturated
 fat varies with negative externalities generated by consuming such goods.
 The answer is most probably positive, as it is likely that the demand would
 decrease with the diseconomies as people with poorer health eat less fatty
 foods.
 In either case, the demand is probably not affected by the demand by others,
 so the externalities are separable from the demand of all other consumers.
 However, one could imagine a situation in which the individual demand for
 unhealthy foods would increase if the aggregate demand for unhealthy food
 was increased.
 This could be the case if unhealthy foods become more readily available
 or that the people in an individual's social circle increase their consumption
 of unhealthy foods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model put forth by Diamond does not take into account the effect already
 mentioned that a tax on one type of unhealthy food might simply move consumptio
n to another type of unhealthy food with the same type of externalities
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 26"
key "sondergaard2011optimal"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the United States there has been several attempts to curb the consumption
 of sugary soft drinks.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Tara Thean, ‘Study: Can a Soda Tax Help Curb Obesity?’, Time, accessed 26
 March 2013, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://healthland.time.com/2011/06/30/study-can-a-soda-tax-help-curb-obesity/"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In Illinois in 2011, a bill was introduced that proposed to add €0.0078
 (a penny) per 28.35 grams (ounce) to the cost of soft drinks.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Andrew Thomason, ‘Soda Tax to Fight Obesity Could Fizzle’, Nwitimes.com,
 11 May 2011, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://www.nwitimes.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/soda-tax-to-fight-obesity-could-fizzle/article_fb4bfffa-f0f7-5bb6-896a-25888d202faa.html"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Imposing a tax is not the only policy solution proposed to limit the consumptio
n of unhealthy foods.
 On 11 March 2013 a similar proposal for a policy limiting the size of sugary
 drinks in New York City was struck down by a judge.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
‘Not Everything Is Worth Doing’, The Economist, 12 March 2013, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2013/03/new-yorks-soda-size-limit"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 No matter the policy response, there is evidence that soda taxes do not
 have the desired effect of helping obese people to lose weight, because
 obese people proportionally consume more diet soda,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hilary Hurd Anyaso, ‘Can Soda Tax Curb Obesity?’, Northwestern University
 News, 27 June 2011, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://www.northwestern.edu/newscenter/stories/2011/06/soda-tax-obesity.html"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 although it naturally would have the effect of helping people who are normal
 weight from becoming obese.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Jessica Tobacman, ‘Research Conflicted on Benefits of Soda Tax in Fighting
 Obesity’, Chicago Tribune, 6 July 2011, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2011-07-06/health/ct-x-0706-soda-tax-20110706_1_obese-kids-obese-adults-childhood-obesity"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Going back to the concepts deployed by Diamond, the separability assumption
 thus holds in this example, because the negative externalities of consuming
 soft drinks affect the demand for soft drinks in the sense that there is
 evidence that obese people shift their consumption to diet coke.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A tax on unhealthy foods can be seen as a Pigouvian tax as it aims to discourage
 the consumption of unhealthy foods that generates negative externalities
 for the society in the form of increased health expenditues.
 Thus it is supposed to increase efficiency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 1244"
key "caraher2005taxingfood"

\end_inset

 identify four ways in which a food tax has been imposed:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

1.
 By raising general revenue as in Valued Added Tax (VAT) in the European
 Union (EU) [...].
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
2.
 By extending VAT to some foods such as those high in fat content and using
 this hypothecated revenue to fund prevention initiatives (i.e.
 the so-called ‘fat tax’).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
3.
 By imposing taxes directly on categories of foodstuffs to impact directly
 on behaviour with an additional function identified for revenues, with
 some or all or the revenues being earmarked for prevention activities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
4.
 By imposing taxes directly on certain foodstuffs with the intent of impacting
 directly on behaviour, with no specific function for revenues.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be argued that the Danish tax falls outside any of these categories.
 Its aim was to affect the consumption behaviour of the Danish population,
 so it would either fall under category three or four above, but because
 the revenue generated was not specifically earmarked for prevention activities,
 it falls outside.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whether the tax was introduced primarily to raise revenue and secondarily
 attempting to affect the behaviour of Danish consumers or vice versa is
 debatable.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See: Kristian Madsen, ‘Nekrolog over den forhadte fedtskat’, Politiken.dk,
 14 November 2012, http://politiken.dk/debat/profiler/kristianmadsen/ECE1812006/n
ekrolog-over-den-forhadte-fedtskat/; and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "pp. 13-4"
key "danishgovernment2009forrarspakke"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The fact that the abolishment was eventually financed by lowering the labour
 tax credit and raising labour income taxes supports the argument that it
 was primarily introduced to raise revenue rather than wholeheartedly trying
 to affect behaviour because the revenue was not destined to be used to
 prevention activities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Disregarding the hierarchy of priorities of the reason for introducing the
 tax, it is clear that the tax was introduced to increase the longevity
 of the Danish population by decreasing the risks of cancer and cardiovascular
 diseases 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 13"
key "danishgovernment2009forrarspakke"

\end_inset

.
 As mentioned above, in other countries the main argument for introducing
 such a tax has been to limit the problems relating to obesity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From a purely health policy perspective there is evidence that that a tax
 on unhealthy foods is effective.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sacks2011textquotelefttrafficlighttextquoteright"

\end_inset

 analyses the cost-effectiveness of policy-based interventions such as a
 tax on unhealthy food to improve obesity prevention.
 They use price elasticities to estimate the change in energy intake in
 response to a 10% price increase and conclude that imposing a tax on unhealthy
 food is both effective and cost-saving as obesity prevention measures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the controversies surrounding the introduction of the Danish tax
 on saturated fats was that it was argued that it hit lower income groups
 relatively harder than higher income groups.
 In this sense the discussion centers upon one of the three Musgravian taxation
 functions, namely income distribution or distributive equity, because the
 discussion relates to the fairness of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the relative distribution of tax shares between various taxpayers
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 215"
key "musgrave1939thevoluntary"

\end_inset

.
 The same argument was echoed in the debate in the US on taxes on sugary
 soft drinks.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Stephen Gandel, ‘Denmark Levies First-Ever Fat Tax, Should the U.S.?’, Time,
 accessed 26 March 2013, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://business.time.com/2011/10/05/denmark-levies-first-ever-fat-tax-should-the-u-s/"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Indeed, there are indications that a tax on unhealthy food is regressive
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 16"
key "leicester2004thefat"

\end_inset

.
 Kaplow 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "kaplow2011thetheory"

\end_inset

, however, argues that consumption taxes should not take into account redistribu
tive questions as this is better dealt with by labour income taxes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 7"
key "sondergaard2011optimal"

\end_inset

.
 Specifically, Kaplow 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
after "p. 17"
key "kaplow2011thetheory"

\end_inset

 argues it is difficult to ascertain whether a specific tax is increasing
 or decreasing redistribution, because the notional amounts might be decreasing
 redistribution, while the proportional amount might be increasing redistributio
n.
 One must look at the the revenues of the tax will be spent to understand
 whether the full implications of the tax levy is regressive, progressive
 or neutral.
 In the Danish case, the imposition of the fat tax was introduced as part
 of a tax reform called 'Spring Package 2.0' (
\emph on
Forårspakke 2.0
\emph default
) that had the two main aims of lowering labour income tax and increasing
 taxes on goods that are harmful to the environment and health 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 3"
key "danishgovernment2009forrarspakke"

\end_inset

.
 Analysis from the Economic Council of the Labour Movement estimated that
 the distributional effects of this reform package was that most income
 groups get their net incomes reduced, while only groups of the population
 with highest income gain from the reforms.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Jonas Schytz Juul, ‘Regeringens kriseregning: Stigende skatter og velfærdstab
 på 12 mia.
 kr.’, Economic Council of the Danish Labour Movement, 31 August 2011, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://ae.dk/analyse/regeringens-kriseregning-stigende-skatter-velfaerdstab-pa-12-mia-kr"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is partly because the reform lowered the top-tier labour income tax
 rate from 63% to 56%.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Danish Chamber of Commerce, ‘Hovedpunkterne i VKO-skattereformen: Forårspakke
 2.0’, accessed 4 April 2013, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "https://www.danskerhverv.dk/Politik/Skat/Skattekommission-skattereform/Sider/Skattekommission-Skattereform.aspx"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Thus, considering that the revenues from the tax on saturated fats is used
 to finance a tax reform that eases the tax burdens of the highest echelons
 of the income hierarchy, the tax on saturated fat can be argued to be regressiv
e.
 This conclusion is supported by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "leicester2004thefat"

\end_inset

 that looks at a fat tax 
\emph on
per se
\emph default
, as opposed to the holistic approach advocated by Kaplow (2011) mentioned
 above.
 They speculate based on the studies by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "blow2004consumption"

\end_inset

 who have shown that alcohol and catering is not consumed evenly along the
 income distribution curve, that this is also the case for fatty foods,
 making the tax in essence regressive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Apart from the negative externalities that the consumption of fatty foods
 may entail, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 1"
key "odonoghue2006optimal"

\end_inset

 point to the problem of over-consumption by replacing the standard assumption
 of full self-control with an assumption that some consumers may lack perfect
 self-control in the consumption of certain goods.
 In a society without self-control problems a tax on fatty foods would simply
 be distortionary to the otherwise optimal consumption of these products.
 They demonstrate that even in the case of little lack of self-control the
 optimal 'sin' tax is quite large.
 Moreover, they use the concept of a 'sin good' 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

that is enjoyable to consume but creates negative health consequences in
 the future.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 One of the results that they derive is that current consumption has negative
 externalities for the future self, which has been named a 'negative internality
' by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "herrnstein1993utility"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first-best solution to the negative internality problem is to impose
 taxes proportional to the degree of self-control problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 2"
key "odonoghue2006optimal"

\end_inset

, but this is not possible so the remaining solution is to impose a uniform,
 linear tax for all consumers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Diamond (1973) analyses uniform taxation to correct non-uniform externalities
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 2"
key "odonoghue2006optimal"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The taxes discussed in the US relate to the size of sugary soft drinks,
 which is arguably linked to obesity, while the Danish tax is on saturated
 relying on the assumption that this is linked to cancer and cardiovascular
 diseases.
 The Prevention Commission assumed that a 1% increase in the proportion
 of the daily energy intake that comes from saturated fats increases the
 risk for cardiovascular disease with 3% 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 149"
key "forebyggelseskommissionen2009vikan"

\end_inset

.
 Both of these two assumptions, i.e.
 correlation between size of soft drinks and obesity as well as a correlation
 between intake of saturated fats and cardiovascular diseases, have however
 been called into question.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Source?
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another reason according to which a tax should be judged is according to
 the change in total welfare, the tax revenue, the loss of output and who
 bears the main burden of the tax.
 In the case of the tax on saturated fats, the tax is supposed to increase
 total welfare.
 Before the tax we had a market failure, where the competitive equilibrium
 did not maximise total welfare.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 567"
key "perloff2011microeconomics"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The social marginal cost of consumption was larger than the private marginal
 cost of consumption, so more was consumed than the amount optimising social
 welfare.
 Regarding the tax revenue, the Prevention Commission estimated in 2009
 that the revenue from imposing a DKK20 per kg would generate DKK0.9-1bn
 (€120.7m-134.1m).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the imposition of a fat tax might have allocative efficiency and
 welfare enhancing outcomes, the evidence from Denmark suggests that it
 also imposes considerable administrative costs on the suppliers.
 Determining whether these costs outweigh the benefits is crucial in understandi
ng the total effects of fat taxes, but difficult to ascertain in practice.
 The administrative burden arises from the requirement that companies selling
 products containing high amounts of saturated fats have to collect the
 tax through higher prices and then pass on the tax to the tax authorities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Price elasticities of the demand of the taxed good are important in order
 to understand the effects of the imposition of a tax.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegge2002oversigt"

\end_inset

 finds that the elasticities for dairy products lie in the interval -1.3
 to -0.2 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 146"
key "forebyggelseskommissionen2009vikan"

\end_inset

.
 This implies that imposing a tax of DKK20 would decrease the consumption
 of saturated fats somewhere in the interval 1.5% and 5.9% according to the
 calculations of the Prevention Commission 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
after "p. 148"
key "forebyggelseskommissionen2009vikan"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imposing a tax on foods containing high amounts of saturated fats may also
 have the effect that producers reduce the amount of fat in their products
 
